Variable Naming Rules:

Must begin with a letter or underscore.

Can contain letters, digits, and underscores.

No special characters or spaces allowed.

3. ğ€ğ’ğ‚ğˆğˆ ğ“ğšğ›ğ¥ğ ğ¢ğ§ ğ‚++

ğ€ğ’ğ‚ğˆğˆ (ğ€ğ¦ğğ«ğ¢ğœğšğ§ ğ’ğ­ğšğ§ğğšğ«ğ ğ‚ğ¨ğğ ğŸğ¨ğ« ğˆğ§ğŸğ¨ğ«ğ¦ğšğ­ğ¢ğ¨ğ§ ğˆğ§ğ­ğğ«ğœğ¡ğšğ§ğ ğ) is a character encoding standard that represents characters as integers. Each character (letters, digits, symbols) has a corresponding ASCII value.

ğ€ğ’ğ‚ğˆğˆ ğ„ğ±ğšğ¦ğ©ğ¥ğ:

The ASCII value of 'A' is 65.

The ASCII value of 'a' is 97.

The ASCII value of '0' is 48.

How to Use ASCII in C++:

Common ASCII Values: 

Character	             ASCII Value
  'A'	                    65
  'a'	                    97
  '0'                     48
  ' '(space)	            32
  '$'	                    36
  '@'	                    64


You can find the ASCII value of any character using type casting:

char ch = 'A';

cout << "The ASCII value of " << ch << " is: " << int(ch) << endl;

Common ASCII Values:

CharacterASCII Value'A'65'a'97'0'48' ' (space)32'$'36'@'644. 

ğ‚ğ¨ğ¦ğ¦ğğ§ğ­ğ¬ ğ¢ğ§ ğ‚++:-

Comments are non-executable lines in the code that help in explaining the purpose or functionality of the code. Comments can make your code more readable and maintainable.

ğ’ğ¢ğ§ğ ğ¥ğ-ğ‹ğ¢ğ§ğ ğ‚ğ¨ğ¦ğ¦ğğ§ğ­ğ¬:

Single-line comments start with // and end at the end of the line.

// ğ“ğ¡ğ¢ğ¬ ğ¢ğ¬ ğš ğ¬ğ¢ğ§ğ ğ¥ğ-ğ¥ğ¢ğ§ğ ğœğ¨ğ¦ğ¦ğğ§ğ­

